      short: [
        {q:"Why do different people have different development goals? Give examples.",a:"DIFFERENT DEVELOPMENT GOALS arise because people have different life situations, needs and aspirations.\n\nEXAMPLES:\n• A LANDLESS LABOURER wants more days of work, higher wages and a house. For them, development means better employment and income security.\n• A RICH FARMER wants higher prices for crops and modern irrigation. Their development goals are about improving agricultural productivity.\n• A GIRL from an educated family may want to study further and have a career — she values education and gender equality.\n• A BUSINESSMAN wants stable government, good infrastructure and easy credit.\n• An ENVIRONMENTALIST wants clean air, forests protected and sustainable use of resources.\n• A TRIBAL PERSON may want their traditional land rights protected.\n\nKEY INSIGHT: What is 'development' for one person may not be for another, or may even HARM others. (e.g. a dam provides water for some but displaces others)\n\nTHEREFORE: We need to look at both INDIVIDUAL goals AND NATIONAL development goals, balancing them."},
        {q:"What is the Human Development Index? How is it different from per capita income?",a:"HUMAN DEVELOPMENT INDEX (HDI):\nDeveloped by UNDP, it measures human development on THREE dimensions:\n1. LONG AND HEALTHY LIFE: Measured by life expectancy at birth\n2. KNOWLEDGE/EDUCATION: Measured by mean years of schooling and expected years of schooling\n3. DECENT STANDARD OF LIVING: Measured by Gross National Income per capita\n\nHDI gives equal weight to all three — a composite index from 0 to 1.\n\nDIFFERENCES FROM PER CAPITA INCOME:\n• Per capita income measures only MONEY; HDI measures money + health + education\n• A country can have high per capita income but poor health/education (Saudi Arabia historically)\n• A country can have good HDI with lower income if it invests in health and education (Kerala, Sri Lanka, Cuba)\n• HDI gives a more complete picture of people's actual well-being\n• Distribution matters in HDI (through health and education outcomes) while per capita income ignores inequality\n\nEXAMPLE: Kerala has lower per capita income than Punjab but higher HDI because of better literacy and life expectancy."},
        {q:"What is sustainable development? Why is it important?",a:"SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT: Development that meets the needs of the present generation without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs.\n\nKEY PRINCIPLES:\n• Use renewable resources at or below their regeneration rate\n• Non-renewable resources should be used sparingly\n• Pollution should not exceed absorptive capacity of environment\n• Diversity (biological and cultural) should be preserved\n\nWHY IMPORTANT:\n1. RESOURCE DEPLETION: Many natural resources (coal, oil, groundwater) are being used faster than they form\n2. ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE: Development activities cause pollution, deforestation, climate change\n3. FUTURE GENERATIONS: Today's overuse leaves less for future generations\n4. EQUITY: Poor countries and peoples bear more of the costs of environmental damage\n5. SURVIVAL: Climate change threatens the survival of many species and communities\n\nEXAMPLE: Groundwater extraction in India exceeds natural recharge rate → falling water tables → threatens agriculture and drinking water for future generations."}
      ],
      long: [
        {q:"'Per capita income is an important indicator of development but has several limitations.' Explain. What are better indicators of development?",a:"PER CAPITA INCOME AS INDICATOR:\n• Measures total national income divided by population\n• Countries classified as Low Income (under $1085), Middle Income ($1086-$13205), High Income (above $13205) by World Bank\n• India is in lower-middle income group; USA is high income\n• Useful for basic comparisons across countries\n\nLIMITATIONS OF PER CAPITA INCOME:\n1. IGNORES DISTRIBUTION: High average income can coexist with extreme inequality. Top 1% can inflate average while most people are poor.\n2. IGNORES QUALITY OF LIFE: Money doesn't capture health, education, freedom, security\n3. IGNORES NON-MONETARY ASPECTS: Clean environment, safe roads, good governance not captured\n4. MEASUREMENT PROBLEMS: Informal economy, unpaid household work not counted\n5. DOESN'T REFLECT SUSTAINABILITY: Income from depleting resources not sustainable\n\nBETTER INDICATORS:\n1. HDI: Combines income, health and education\n2. INFANT MORTALITY RATE: How many children survive — reflects health services\n3. LITERACY RATE: Education access and quality\n4. LIFE EXPECTANCY: Reflects overall health and well-being\n5. NET ATTENDANCE RATIO: Children in school\n6. GINI COEFFICIENT: Measures inequality\n7. MATERNAL MORTALITY RATE: Women's health\n\nEXAMPLE: Kerala vs Haryana:\n• Haryana has higher per capita income\n• Kerala has BETTER health and education indicators\n• Kerala shows that investment in health and education gives better human development even with lower income"}
      ],
      passage: [
        {q:"Study the following data:\n\nCountry A: Per capita income $2000, Life expectancy 75 years, Literacy rate 90%\nCountry B: Per capita income $8000, Life expectancy 55 years, Literacy rate 50%\n\n(a) Which country has better HDI? Why?\n(b) What does this tell us about the relationship between income and development?\n(c) How can Country B improve its development?\n(d) What is meant by 'public facilities'? Give two examples.",a:"(a) Country A has BETTER HDI despite lower per capita income because:\n• HDI measures three dimensions: income + health + education\n• Country A has much higher life expectancy (75 vs 55 years)\n• Country A has much higher literacy rate (90% vs 50%)\n• In HDI terms, Country A's people live longer and are better educated — higher human development\n\n(b) This tells us that INCOME ALONE does not determine development:\n• High income can coexist with poor health and education (Country B)\n• Even with moderate income, countries can achieve high human development if they invest wisely in health and education (Country A)\n• Sri Lanka and Kerala are real examples — high human development with relatively lower income\n• Public investment in health and education is more important than raw income levels\n\n(c) Country B can improve development by:\n• Investing more government spending in public health (hospitals, healthcare access)\n• Expanding public education system — building schools, training teachers\n• Reducing inequality so that high income reaches more people\n• Creating public facilities like clean water, sanitation\n• Social programmes targeting literacy among women and marginalised groups\n\n(d) Public facilities are services provided by the government for all citizens, not for profit:\n• Examples: Public schools, public hospitals, public transport, clean water supply, electricity, roads\n• These cannot be provided adequately by private markets alone because poor people cannot afford them\n• They are essential for human development"}
      ]
